# 📅 Day 10 – C++ Fundamentals

# 1️⃣ Polymorphism (One Thing, Many Forms)

---

# First Understand the Big Idea

The word:

```text id="i5m0ha"
Poly = many
Morph = forms
```

So:

# Polymorphism means:

👉 Same function behaves differently in different situations.

---

# Real-World Example

Think of this word:

```text id="g8yq0m"
“Run”
```

Different meanings:

* Human runs
* Car runs
* Machine runs

Same word → different behavior.

That’s polymorphism.

---

# Why Polymorphism Exists

Without it:

```text id="qjlwm7"
dogSound()
catSound()
birdSound()
```

Too many separate functions ❌

With polymorphism:

```text id="jlwmc2"
sound()
```

One interface, different behavior ✅

---

# Types of Polymorphism

| Type         | When                       |
| ------------ | -------------------------- |
| Compile-time | decided during compilation |
| Run-time     | decided during execution   |

---

# Part A — Compile-Time Polymorphism

Achieved using:

# ⭐ Function Overloading

---

# Function Overloading

---

## Simple Idea

👉 Same function name with different parameters.

---

# Example

```cpp id="0jlwm7"
class Math
{
public:

    int add(int a, int b)
    {
        return a + b;
    }

    int add(int a, int b, int c)
    {
        return a + b + c;
    }
};
```

---

# What Happens?

Compiler checks:

```text id="wjlwm1"
How many arguments?
What type?
```

Then chooses correct function.

---

# Mental Model

```text id="sjlwm8"
Same worker → different jobs depending on input
```

---

# Real-World Example

Phone camera app:

```text id="fjlwm2"
Photo()
Photo(filter)
Photo(filter, brightness)
```

Same action, different versions.

---

# Why It Works

Because function signatures differ:

```text id="6jlwmf"
name + parameters
```

---

# Common Mistake 🔥

Only changing return type is NOT overloading.

❌ Wrong:

```cpp id="2jlwmv"
int fun()
float fun()
```

Compiler gets confused.

---

# How to Remember

```text id="tjlwm5"
Overloading = same name, different inputs
```

---

# Part B — Run-Time Polymorphism

Achieved using:

# ⭐ Function Overriding + Virtual Functions

This is VERY IMPORTANT for interviews.

---

# Function Overriding

---

## Simple Idea

👉 Child class changes parent class function behavior.

---

# Example

```cpp id="hjlwm9"
class Animal
{
public:

    void sound()
    {
        cout << "Animal Sound";
    }
};

class Dog : public Animal
{
public:

    void sound()
    {
        cout << "Bark";
    }
};
```

---

# What Happens?

Dog provides its OWN version of:

```text id="qjlwm3"
sound()
```

---

# Mental Model

```text id="h7lm0p"
Parent gives general behavior
Child customizes it
```

---

# Real-World Example

Vehicle:

```text id="z0lwm2"
Vehicle start()
```

Different implementations:

* Bike start
* Car start
* Bus start

---

# Problem Without Virtual Function

Now VERY IMPORTANT concept.

---

# Example

```cpp id="9jlwm8"
Animal* ptr;
Dog d;

ptr = &d;

ptr->sound();
```

Without `virtual`:

Output:

```text id="jlwmz1"
Animal Sound
```

NOT Bark.

Why?

Because compiler checks pointer type:

```text id="2jlwm0"
Animal*
```

---

# Solution → Virtual Function

---

# Example

```cpp id="4jlwmf"
class Animal
{
public:

    virtual void sound()
    {
        cout << "Animal Sound";
    }
};
```

Now output becomes:

```text id="jlwmu5"
Bark
```

---

# Why Virtual Works

With virtual:

👉 Decision delayed until runtime.

Computer checks:

```text id="mjlwm9"
actual object type
```

not pointer type.

---

# Mental Model (VERY IMPORTANT)

```text id="jlwm6r"
virtual = decide later at runtime
```

---

# Visualization

Without virtual:

```text id="9jlwmk"
Pointer type decides
```

With virtual:

```text id="jlwm4z"
Actual object decides
```

---

# Why Virtual Functions Matter

They enable:

* flexibility
* dynamic behavior
* real-world software architecture

Used heavily in:

* game engines
* UI systems
* frameworks

---

# Key Difference

| Overloading          | Overriding           |
| -------------------- | -------------------- |
| same class           | parent-child classes |
| compile time         | runtime              |
| different parameters | same parameters      |

---

# Common Interview Question 🔥

# Why Use Virtual Function?

Answer:

```text id="jjlwm2"
To achieve runtime polymorphism.
```

---

# How to Remember Forever

```text id="jlwm3m"
Overloading → same name, different inputs
Overriding → same function, different behavior
Virtual → runtime decision
```

